We can “build” the fixed‐assets net as follows. First, the initial entry shows that the company started with a “Fixed Assets” amount of 5,000,000.00.

Then several “Fixed Assets Purchase” transactions were recorded on 2023‑12‑31. In our file their amounts are:

 • 230,120.87  
 • 478,737.63  
 • 351,585.30  
 • 386,528.93  

Summing these additions:
 230,120.87 + 478,737.63 = 708,858.50  
Adding the third amount: 708,858.50 + 351,585.30 = 1,060,443.80  
And adding the fourth: 1,060,443.80 + 386,528.93 = 1,446,972.73

These represent the additional fixed assets introduced on top of the initial value.

We must subtract the accumulated depreciation – there is one depreciation transaction:
 • Depreciation20240101001 = 45,742.50

Thus, the final (end‑of‑period) net fixed assets is computed as:

 Initial Fixed Assets + Total Additions − Depreciation  
 = 5,000,000.00 + 1,446,972.73 − 45,742.50  
 = 6,446,972.73 − 45,742.50  
 = 6,401,230.23
